{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Command segmentation treats newline-separated statements as separate segments, not one monolithic block.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Failure boundary is local parsing/segmentation logic on a command string (no module handoff required to reproduce). REAL-INFRA is absent: no OS/network/subprocess needed. LLM-DEP and MULTI-STEP are absent. Rejected higher level because behavior text is strictly about segmentation, not cross-module persistence or external execution.","test_description":"Unit-test the segmentation function with input like `BRANCH=x\\nTITLE=y\\ngh pr create ...`; assert it returns distinct ordered segments (assignments and command separated) rather than one combined block.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A multi-line shell block with variable assignments followed by `gh pr create` is recognized as a PR-create trigger.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure appears at module boundary: segmenter output must be consumed correctly by trigger-classification logic (MOCK-MISS). Unit tests of matcher alone can miss handoff bugs like the incident. Integration brake: no real OS/network/subprocess required, so not System; no AI output dependence, so not Agentic/Workflow.","test_description":"Integration test wiring segmentation + trigger detection in-process: feed a multiline command block with assignments then `gh pr create`; assert classification is `pr_create_trigger` (not `not_a_trigger`).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A similar multi-line block that ends with `gh issue create` is not incorrectly treated as a PR-create trigger.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is negative classification correctness across segmented-command handoff, not just a single regex check. Need segmenter+classifier together to catch false-positive boundary bugs. Rejected System because behavior text is command interpretation only, not real `gh` execution. Rejected Agentic/Workflow because no model decisions.","test_description":"Integration test with multiline assignments + `gh issue create`; run through full in-process segmentation/classification path; assert result is non-PR trigger and no PR-review-loop activation flag is set.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When a PR-create trigger is detected, the hook can reconstruct and persist the PR identifier needed by the review loop state.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Requires interaction between trigger handling, PR-id extraction, and state persistence modules/filesystem path handling. Real failure is often in handoff/serialization, not isolated logic. Integration brake: local filesystem write/read is sufficient; behavior does not require real subprocess/network, so System is not mandatory. No AI dependency.","test_description":"Integration test in a temp directory: simulate detected PR-create event plus representative hook payload containing PR URL/number; run post-hook handler; assert persisted state file contains the expected reconstructed PR identifier and required fields.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"After PR-create detection, the review gate state is written in a form that the pre-tool enforcement hook can read and enforce.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is explicit cross-module contract validation (PostToolUse writer -> PreToolUse reader/enforcer). Unit tests per m